===Etymology 1===
{{PIE root|en|lewbʰ}}
From {{inh|en|enm|love}}, {{m|enm|luve}}, from {{inh|en|ang|lufu|t=love, affection, desire}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*lubō|t=love}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*lewbʰ-|t=love, care, desire}}. Cognate with {{cog|ofs|luve|t=love}}, {{cog|goh|luba|t=love}}. Related to {{cog|ang|lēof|t=dear, beloved}}, {{m|ang|līefan|t=to allow, approve of}}, {{cog|is|ljúfur|t=dear; beloved; sweet; gentle}}, {{cog|stq|Ljoowe|t=love}}, {{cog|la|libet}}, {{m|la|lubō|t=to please}} and {{cog|sa|लुभ्यति|tr=lúbhyati||to desire}}, {{cog|sq|lyp|t=to beg, ask insistently}}, {{m|sq|lips|t=to be demanded, needed}}, {{cog|sh|ljubiti}}, {{m|sh|ljubav}}, {{cog|ru|любо́вь}}, {{m|ru|люби́ть}}.

The closing-of-a-letter sense is presumably a truncation of ''With love'' or the like.

The verb is from {{inh|en|enm|loven}}, {{m|enm|lovien}}, from {{inh|en|ang|lufian|t=to love, cherish, sow love to; fondle, caress; delight in, approve, practice}}, from the noun {{m|ang|lufu|t=love}}. See above. Compare {{cog|fy|leavje|t=to love}}, {{cog|de|lieben|t=to love}}, {{cog|is|lofa|t=to prize}} and {{m|is|loforð|t=a promise}}.

